<h2>Massachusetts Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Massachusetts offers some of the most comprehensive renewable energy and energy efficiency incentives in the United States, making solar and HVAC upgrades highly attractive financially. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and related expenses, providing substantial upfront savings for Massachusetts homeowners.</p>

<p>The state's Solar Massachusetts Renewable Target (SMART) program replaced the previous SREC program and provides long-term performance-based incentives. SMART offers a fixed rate per kilowatt-hour produced over 10 years for residential systems up to 25kW. The current base compensation rate varies by utility territory and system size, typically ranging from \$0.06 to \$0.10 per kWh for residential installations. Additional adders are available for energy storage systems, affordable housing, and brownfield installations.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, Massachusetts provides rebates through the Mass Save program, a collaboration between utility companies including Eversource, National Grid, and municipal utilities. Heat pump rebates range from \$1,250 to \$10,000 depending on system type and efficiency. Central air conditioning systems with SEER ratings of 16 or higher qualify for rebates up to \$400. Ductless mini-split systems receive rebates of \$300-\$500 per indoor unit. Additional incentives are available for whole-house weatherization, programmable thermostats, and smart HVAC controls.</p>

<p>Eversource, serving much of eastern Massachusetts, offers enhanced rebates through their Green Communities program and provides zero-interest financing options for qualifying energy efficiency improvements. The utility also participates in time-of-use rate programs that can increase solar savings by providing higher compensation for electricity fed back to the grid during peak demand periods. Property tax exemptions are available for solar installations, and the increased home value from solar systems is exempt from property tax assessments.</p>

